      },
      "date": "2014-01-07 23:58:11.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nAndreas, Some quick tests show that the cost of the patch with no modifications is between 18 - 21%. Let me work on this a bit and see if I can get that cost down. \n\nAlso, I have a fix for when setstripe is called with a pool name. I'll upload the complete solution when I get the run time down.\n\nThanks for the comment, James",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "cbbd40b81d04f3d2e12e19cc175c3c77e9548609",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 292,
        "name": "James Nunez",
        "email": "jnunez@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jnunez"
      },
      "date": "2014-01-17 23:53:55.000000000",
      "message": "Uploaded patch set 3.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "263d9fd952d788991774742c4bbb32ca9368ab9e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 292,
        "name": "James Nunez",
        "email": "jnunez@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jnunez"
      },
      "date": "2014-01-18 00:24:17.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nI've uploaded a new patch that takes case when an OST index that is out of range of the file system's OSTs. For the case where a users specifies the pool name (-p | --pool) and the OST index, checking that the OST index is in the pool does not add much time.\nWhen checking the OST index with no pool specified for 30,000 files, this modification can add ~20% to the run time; from ~100 sec. to ~120 sec. (wall clock). The caching in llapi_search_fsname does not help this case of 30,000 individual calls to 'lfs setstrip' in a loop.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
